<section class="card">
  <h2>About Cucumbers</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Warm-season vines—heat accumulation and frost timing determine viability.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Cucumbers are frost-tender and killed at 32°F (0°C).</strong>
    In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), cucumber success depends on planting into warm soil, accumulating enough Growing Degree Days (GDD), and finishing before first fall frost.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, cucumbers can perform well if started into warm conditions and given full sun. The most common failure mode is early-season cold that delays growth and reduces risk margin before frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Direct sow:</strong> 2–4 weeks after last frost (once soil is warm)</li>
    <li><strong>Indoor start (optional):</strong> 3–4 weeks before transplant window</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 45–70 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> None (killed at 32°F / 0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are planning baselines. Soil warmth and steady heat strongly influence actual maturity timing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Temperature & Soil Requirements</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Minimum soil temperature:</strong> ~60°F (16°C) for reliable germination</li>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 70–90°F (21–32°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below 60°F (16°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Freeze damage:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Cucumbers stall quickly in cool soil or cold nights. Early planting into marginal conditions often delays development enough to reduce fall buffer.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    If you want a reminder of what frost dates represent in climate planning (not forecasts), see:
    <a href="/guides/average-frost-date-vs-actual-weather/">Average frost date vs actual weather</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~900–1,200 GDD (base 50) for many slicing and pickling types</p>

  <p>
    Cucumbers mature on accumulated seasonal heat. In cooler summers, labeled “55-day” varieties may take longer if GDD accumulation is weak.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For the full frost + heat framework, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Most cucumber varieties require <strong>45–70 frost-free days</strong> to begin harvest.
    However, cool early growth can extend the effective timeline and shrink your margin before first frost.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Yes, with warm planting conditions and early varieties</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Sometimes, especially if spring soil warms slowly</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Occasionally helpful early (row cover for warmth), but heat accumulation is the main driver</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Cucumbers have no frost tolerance buffer. A freeze at 32°F (0°C) can end the crop immediately.
    First frost is therefore a hard maturity boundary.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Select early varieties (45–55 day types)</li>
    <li>Wait for warm soil before direct sowing</li>
    <li>Use black mulch or full-sun sites to increase soil warmth</li>
    <li>Protect early transplants from wind and cold nights</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, cucumbers are viable when your frost-free window provides enough time and your seasonal heat budget provides enough GDD for flowering and fruit set before 32°F (0°C).
    Early-season cold is the most common way risk margin disappears.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can cucumbers survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    No. Cucumbers are frost-sensitive and can be damaged or killed at 32°F (0°C).
  </p>

  <h3>Why are my cucumbers slow to grow?</h3>
  <p>
    Most often, soil or night temperatures are too cool. Weak early growth can delay flowering and reduce maturity buffer.
  </p>

  <h3>Are cucumbers easier than corn in short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    Usually yes. Cucumbers require fewer GDD than sweet corn, but still depend on consistent heat accumulation to finish before frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Typical requirement: 45–70 days, ~900–1,200 GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Warm soil at planting preserves risk margin.</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + buffer.</li>
  </ul>
</section>